The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Bengal | Briefs
                                                                                                                     4                                                                                      BRIEFS
                  
	Calcutta, Aug. 11: Chief minister Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee today discussed with governor M.K. Narayanan the law and order situation in the state, particularly Lalgarh where Mamata Banerjee held a rally on Monday.    
	Bhattacharjee reportedly spoke about the Peoples Committee Against Police Atrocities participation in the rally. Raj Bhavan sources said the chief minister had himself sought the appointment with Narayanan. Narayanan could visit Lalgarh, the sources added.        
	Burdwan: A youth was arrested for allegedly drugging and robbing a passenger on the Howrah-bound Kalka Mail. Motazul Sheikh, 25, had befriended mason Mafikul Mondal, given him drug-laced soft drinks and robbed him after he fell asleep. Mondal, who was returning from Delhi, searched the compartment after he woke up on Wednesday morning and spotted Sheikh in the crowd. Sheikh had boarded the train from Mughalsarai.        
	Bankura: A Trinamul Congress worker was killed and another injured in a clash with CPM supporters in Bankuras Patrashayar on Wednesday. Sheikh Badri Alam, 50, died after taking two bullets in the neck. Sumantra Adhikari, the officer in charge of the local police station, was suspended for not being able to stop frequent political clashes in the area.        
	Bolpur: Monirul Islam, the vice-president of the Trinamul Congress in Birbhum, was arrested on Wednesday in connection with the murder of six CPM workers in the district.
                                                                                                                                                      
